# {{lb|en|grammar}} A [[verb]] form that indicates an ongoing action or state in the present and which can function as an [[adjective]].

====Usage notes====
In English, a present participle is formed by adding the suffix '''[[-ing]]''' to the stem of a verb. A participle can be preceded with a form of the verb ''to [[be]]'' to make what is called the [[progressive tense]]s. When a participle functions as a noun, it is called a '''[[gerund]]'''. A participle may also function as an adjective, especially in [[attributive]] use. It can evolve to become either a true [[noun]] or a true [[adjective]], or both, with a shift in meaning, sometimes substantial. To see examples, look for words ending in “[[-ing]]” in [[:Category:English adjectives]] and [[:Category:English nouns]].

